00:06:02.420 --> 00:06:03.800
Are you working on one of them?

00:06:03.800 --> 00:06:05.150
Why not?

00:06:05.150 --> 00:06:12.222
I love that, and that's very
much an MIT ecosystem way,

00:06:12.222 --> 00:06:13.430
but it's not true everywhere.

00:06:13.430 --> 00:06:15.140
But we should always
remind ourselves,

00:06:15.140 --> 00:06:17.410
even if I solve this problem--

00:06:17.410 --> 00:06:19.160
so I'd say, my problem
is I want to change

00:06:19.160 --> 00:06:22.530
the bandgap of silicon
from indirect to direct.

00:06:22.530 --> 00:06:23.030
OK?

00:06:23.030 --> 00:06:25.010
I can do that now,
because we've learned how

00:06:25.010 --> 00:06:26.380
to do that using simulation.

00:06:26.380 --> 00:06:29.120
So I can probe materials
using a computer.

00:06:29.120 --> 00:06:32.210
You should still say, why?

00:06:32.210 --> 00:06:34.490
The point isn't-- you
can't just say, why?

00:06:34.490 --> 00:06:36.380
Well, because it
would be useful.

00:06:36.380 --> 00:06:38.770
Or why, well, because it can
make a better solar cell.

00:06:38.770 --> 00:06:39.570
That's not enough.

00:06:39.570 --> 00:06:40.070
Right?

00:06:40.070 --> 00:06:43.490
It's really how much
impact can you have?

00:06:43.490 --> 00:06:46.400
What is this going to do to the
technology you're working on

00:06:46.400 --> 00:06:49.070
or the science problem
you're trying to answer?

00:06:49.070 --> 00:06:51.500
And taking it those extra
steps goes a long way,

00:06:51.500 --> 00:06:53.390
and that applies
to computing, just

00:06:53.390 --> 00:06:56.022
like any other area of research.

00:06:56.022 --> 00:06:57.980
Better to solve the right
problem the wrong way

00:06:57.980 --> 00:07:00.370
than the wrong
problem the right way.

00:07:00.370 --> 00:07:02.830
So choosing the problem
that's a related statement.

00:07:02.830 --> 00:07:04.760
In research, if you
know what you're doing,

00:07:04.760 --> 00:07:06.460
then you shouldn't be doing it.

00:07:06.460 --> 00:07:12.160
I like that a lot,
and that's where

00:07:12.160 --> 00:07:15.100
computation is a real enabler.

00:07:15.100 --> 00:07:21.610
I love experiments too, but I
love the world of computation,

00:07:21.610 --> 00:07:23.200
especially at this scale.

00:07:23.200 --> 00:07:25.150
Where you can design--

00:07:25.150 --> 00:07:26.860
within a limited
number of atoms--

00:07:26.860 --> 00:07:28.510
you can design anything.

00:07:28.510 --> 00:07:31.090
You can think up
anything and try it.

00:07:31.090 --> 00:07:31.660
Right?

00:07:31.660 --> 00:07:35.260
So there's really the phase
space is just enormous,

00:07:35.260 --> 00:07:37.840
and you can really
play around and try

00:07:37.840 --> 00:07:41.630
crazy ideas, random thoughts,
and tangents out as you go.

00:07:41.630 --> 00:07:44.530
Those are often where the
best creativity happens.

00:07:44.530 --> 00:07:45.680
And then this is it.

00:07:45.680 --> 00:07:46.180
Right?

00:07:46.180 --> 00:07:47.200
Machines should work.

00:07:47.200 --> 00:07:48.910
People should think.

00:07:48.910 --> 00:07:52.803
So as you go after this
class, and you come out,

00:07:52.803 --> 00:07:54.970
one of the most important
things to come out of this

00:07:54.970 --> 00:07:57.970
is it's always a balance.

00:07:57.970 --> 00:08:00.460
When you do computation,
it's a balance

00:08:00.460 --> 00:08:04.150
between your time and
the computer's time.

00:08:04.150 --> 00:08:07.630
And what you'd like
to do is create

00:08:07.630 --> 00:08:09.340
a balance, such
that the computer is

00:08:09.340 --> 00:08:12.460
solving things for you.

00:08:12.460 --> 00:08:15.580
And you're spending most of your
time not solving those things,

00:08:15.580 --> 00:08:19.330
not wasting your time on things
that the computer could do,

00:08:19.330 --> 00:08:21.550
but rather on thinking
about the kind of problem

00:08:21.550 --> 00:08:23.140
that you're going to make it do.

00:08:23.140 --> 00:08:27.250
And you'd be surprised how often
in computation this balance

00:08:27.250 --> 00:08:28.840
is not well kept.

00:08:28.840 --> 00:08:29.640
OK?

00:08:29.640 --> 00:08:33.100
And how often you might
spend a lot of your time

00:08:33.100 --> 00:08:36.730
actually spinning your
wheels on something

00:08:36.730 --> 00:08:38.620
that the machine
could actually handle.

00:08:38.620 --> 00:08:40.480
Right?

00:08:40.480 --> 00:08:42.580
And how much you might
think the machine

00:08:42.580 --> 00:08:44.500
is actually going
to somehow solve

00:08:44.500 --> 00:08:48.640
a problem that actually you
need to think about to solve.

00:08:48.640 --> 00:08:51.130
Or how much more quickly you
could solve it, if you just

00:08:51.130 --> 00:08:52.330
thought for an hour.

00:08:52.330 --> 00:08:55.640
You might have saved a million
hours of computer time.

00:08:55.640 --> 00:08:56.250
Right?

00:08:56.250 --> 00:09:00.350
Seriously, so that balance
always has to be kept in mind.

