00:50:53.700 --> 00:50:55.800
along a line in
this Brillouin zone.

00:50:55.800 --> 00:51:01.160
But what if I had gone like this
or what if I'd done like this?

00:51:01.160 --> 00:51:03.500
Would I get
different curvatures?

00:51:03.500 --> 00:51:06.830
You better believe it.

00:51:06.830 --> 00:51:10.520
You are taking paths
through the Brillouin zone

00:51:10.520 --> 00:51:11.900
to get the band structure.

00:51:11.900 --> 00:51:16.100
That's how you get
the band structure.

00:51:16.100 --> 00:51:25.000
Now, what ends up happening is
that the interesting variations

00:51:25.000 --> 00:51:28.390
in these energy bands,
the interesting ones,

00:51:28.390 --> 00:51:30.670
the ones that are important
for optical and electronic

00:51:30.670 --> 00:51:33.640
properties, tend to happen
between the high-symmetry

00:51:33.640 --> 00:51:35.200
points in the Brillouin zone.

00:51:35.200 --> 00:51:38.200
They tend to happen between
the origin and the center

00:51:38.200 --> 00:51:41.770
of this face and the
center of this edge

00:51:41.770 --> 00:51:43.870
and going back to an origin.

00:51:43.870 --> 00:51:48.640
They tend to happen between the
path of one high-symmetry point

00:51:48.640 --> 00:51:49.760
to another.

00:51:49.760 --> 00:51:54.250
And so, de facto,
we just don't care

00:51:54.250 --> 00:51:56.800
much about everything
else in the Brillouin zone

00:51:56.800 --> 00:52:00.440
because it doesn't really
give us extra information.

00:52:00.440 --> 00:52:02.720
It would give us a
different band structure.

00:52:02.720 --> 00:52:04.550
But it's not that--

00:52:04.550 --> 00:52:08.660
it's not giving us
something that's

00:52:08.660 --> 00:52:11.540
as relevant to the key
fundamental properties

00:52:11.540 --> 00:52:14.190
we care about.

00:52:14.190 --> 00:52:16.170
So that's one thing.

00:52:16.170 --> 00:52:17.930
Now-- so that's where those--

00:52:17.930 --> 00:52:20.150
